<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> JAPAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Reaffirms Nation's Nonnuclear Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Reaffirms Nation's Nonnuclear Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704214494 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 6 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0704214494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 5 April, the government decided to seek the 
international community's positive understanding once again of 
Japan's position that it will maintain its "three nonnuclear 
principles" [of not producing, possessing, and introducing 
nuclear arms] in the future, and that Japan will never be armed 
with nuclear weapons in any form. On the same day, the Monju 
fast-breeder reactor, which produces plutonium, reached 
"criticality." Under this situation, the government made the 
aforementioned decision while taking into consideration the 
possibility that the "concern over Japan becoming a nuclear 
power," which lingers in connection with the suspicions over the 
DPRK's (North Korea) nuclear weapons development program, may 
crop up again. In concrete terms, the government intends to 
make its appeals concerning Japan's position as the "only nation 
in the world that has suffered atomic bombings" through various 
opportunities such as summit meetings and the public relations 
activities of embassies and legations abroad. 
  Last year, Japan's delayed decision to support the 
indefinite 
extension of the nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT) created 
speculation among European nations and the United States that 
Japan "might intend to possess nuclear arms." This was the 
origin of the prevailing view that Japan "will be armed with 
nuclear weapons." 
  Moreover, in connection with North Korea's suspected nuclear 
weapons development, Britain's SUNDAY TIMES newspaper reported 
in January, "The British Ministry of Defense has completed a 
secret report that says there is a possibility that Japan will 
abandon its nonnuclear principles." In the United States, 
Defense Secretary (then Deputy Secretary) William Perry 
testified at a public hearing of the Senate Armed Services 
Committee in February, "If North Korea succeeds in producing 
nuclear weapons, the possibility that Japan, Taiwan, and South 
Korea will seek to possess nuclear arms will increase greatly." 
In this way, there have been statements pointing out the fear 
that Japan will arm itself with nuclear weapons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-67736 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptnd003__l94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
