<DOCNO> FBIS4-67749 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptnd003__l94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TND-94-003-L </AU>
JPRS 
PROLIFERATION ISSUES 

<DATE1>  30 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> KAZAKHSTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nazarbayev Rules Out Nuclear Testing at Semipalatinsk </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nazarbayev Rules Out Nuclear Testing at Semipalatinsk </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3003144594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1314 GMT 30 Mar 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD3003144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] There can be no question of resuming nuclear tests 
at the Semipalatinsk test site, Kazakh leader Nursultan 
Nazarbayev told Russian mass media leaders in Moscow on 
Wednesday. 
  He said as many as 526 aerial, surface and underground 
nuclear blasts had been carried out in eastern Kazakhstan in the 
past 40 years. An estimated 500,000 people fell victim to the 
tests and serious environmental damage was caused. 
  "Kazakhstan has so far been left alone to face those 
problems. The Russian president and I discussed this at length 
and I can now say with confidence that Russia will help us in 
utilizing that large scientific complex for peaceful purposes. 
For example, the Semipalatinsk site can be used for testing 
safety systems of the nuclear power plants or as a space 
training center in concert with Baikonur," Nazarbayev said. 
  At the same time, he called for an international commission 
to be set up, Russia included, to assess the volume and nature 
of damage caused to the people and environment. "This can at 
least help set priorities in eliminating the harmful effects 
from testing," Nazarbayev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

