<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Reports Prevention of Nuclear Technology Exports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rexrodt Reports Prevention of Nuclear Technology Exports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304182594 Hamburg DPA in German 1633 GMT 13 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1304182594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn (DPA) -- In the struggle against arms 
exports, the Cologne Customs Office of Criminal Investigations 
has prevented 11 major cases of violations by German suppliers 
since October 1992. On the occasion of the current parliamentary 
discussions on the renewed amendment to the Foreign Economy Law, 
FRG Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt (Free Democratic Party of 
Germany) noted in a position paper, which became known on 
Wednesday [13 April]: "The greatest success consists in catching 
the main German supplier for the nuclear program of a foreign 
country and uncovering his acquisition organization in Germany 
and Western Europe." According to industrial circles, the 
country could be Pakistan. 
  In four of the 11 cases involved intentional violations of 
the Military Materiel Control Law and one case involved the 
planned delivery of military goods to Iraq. In the other cases 
there was "the suspicion of planned subcontractor deliveries for 
nuclear and missile programs of various sensitive countries." 
With these explanations Rexrodt wanted to justify his stricter 
legal stipulations in the field of telecommunications secrecy 
and fines. The Bundestag Economics Committee, however, postponed 
its deliberations on this matter at short notice. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

