<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-67769 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptnd003__l94038" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TND-94-003-L </AU>
JPRS 
PROLIFERATION ISSUES 

<DATE1>  12 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL </F>
<F P=101></F>
<H3> <TI>     EP Reaffirms Importance of Nuclear Safety in Eastern Europe </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EP Reaffirms Importance of Nuclear Safety in Eastern Europe </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1403101394 Brussels EUROPE in English 12 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1403101394 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels EUROPE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Eastern Europe -- Parliament </F>
Approves EU Contribution to EBRD's "Nuclear Safety" Account"; as 
released by Brussels Textline database] 
  [Text] Reinforcing nuclear safety in the countries of 
Eastern Europe is a matter of great importance to the European 
Parliament, which has followed its rapporteur Mr. Adam (Soc, UK) 
and approved the Council's proposal of contributing 20 million 
Ecus to the "nuclear safety" account set up with the European 
Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD). In his report, 
Mr. Adam states that the first operations done in this area by 
the EBRD in Bulgaria and Lithuania seem to meet EP criteria. 
The next operations in Russia are a test of the EBRD's strategy 
and are therefore to be closely monitored by the Community 
institutions. The sums in question were included in the 1993 
budget but were not committed because there was no legal base. 
They are included in the 1994 budget as a token entry, and if 
the 1993 appropriations are to be used this year, a decision 
will have to be made before the end of March. 
  The EP wants the operations in question to be included in a 
strategic and safety action plan negotiated with the beneficiary 
countries (which should respect the main international 
agreements of security) and the interested countries to be 
endowed with an independent body responsible for safety. It 
also called for the early closure of the plants the least safe. 
During the debate, Mr. Bettini (Greens, It) criticized the 
report, calling for large-scale reconversion to "clean" energy, 
as Mr. Shevardnadze himself had proposed for all of Georgia's 
energy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

