<H3> <TI>   BDI Demands Relaxation Of Arms Export Regulations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    BDI Demands Relaxation Of Arms Export Regulations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1004184494 Berlin DIE WELT in German 9 Apr 94 p 14 </F>
<F P=103> AU1004184494 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [``rmc''-signed report: ``BDI For Relaxing Arms Exports''] </F>
  [Text] Bonn -- The Federation of German Industries (BDI) 
has demanded a relaxation of the strict German arms export 
regulations. The demand was precipitated by the government's new 
white book on security policy and Bundeswehr matters that 
declares the existence of a ``modern, competitive and efficient 
arms industry to be a part of security precautions.'' The BDI 
tells Bonn that this is ``not possible at zero cost and without 
political compromise within the alliance in adjusting arms 
regulations.'' The BDI refers to the uncompromising position of 
some important European partner countries that have refused to 
follow the strict German regulations. The German arms industry 
will only regain its international competitiveness if the 
Federal Government abolishes ``the marked disadvantage that 
German companies are experiencing.'' 

</TEXT>

